<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-817-892  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 817 892.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  Oct 31 1989 pA1(W) pA1(E) 48 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>One high-tech race where U.S. leads: personal computers; otherwiseformidable Japan is surprisingly laggard in automating itsoffices; a case of 'keyboard allergy.' (microcomputers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schlesinger, Jacob M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Japanese companies are finally automating their offices to theextent that their manufacturing plants are: the microcomputer hasarrived.andP;  While manufacturing firms are heavy with robotic andcomputer equipment, Japanese offices have remained labor-intensiveand extremely low in productivity.andP;  At the Ministry ofInternational Trade and Industry's Machinery and InformationIndustries Bureau, 24 people share one microcomputer.andP;  Companiesare beginning to automate, however.andP;  Microcomputer sales in Japanin the first six months of 1989 were 34 percent higher than thesame period in 1988.andP;  One company has spent roughly one-year'sprofits to double the number of microcomputers in its office.andP;  Theprocess is going to take time.andP;  A proper ratio of microcomputersin an office is one thing; proper software and efficient usage ofthe equipment is another.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersJapanOffice Automation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>